A long string of hexadecimal characters is provided. Every two characters in a hex string typically represent one byte of data.
The goal is to convert this hex string back into its original byte format to reveal the flag.

The Hex String:
63727970746f7b596f755f77696c6c5f62655f776f726b696e675f776974685f6865785f737472696e67735f615f6c6f747d

Python provides a built-in method, bytes.fromhex(), which automatically handles the conversion from a hex string to actual bytes.

hex_string = "63727970746f7b596f755f77696c6c5f62655f776f726b696e675f776974685f6865785f737472696e67735f615f6c6f747d"

# Convert hex to bytes
flag_bytes = bytes.fromhex(hex_string)

# Print the decoded result
print(flag_bytes.decode())

Base-16: Unlike our standard decimal system (Base-10), Hexadecimal uses 16 symbols. This is efficient for computers because one byte (8 bits) can be perfectly represented by exactly two hex digits (ranging from 00 to ff).

From Hex to Text: The process follows a specific chain:

Hex Pairs: 63

Decimal Value: 99

ASCII Character: c

bytes.fromhex(): This function parses the string and groups the characters into pairs to create a bytes object. Using .decode() at the end turns those bytes into a standard Python string.
